  "notes": "Nawat (Pipil) — Uto-Aztecan (Nahuan) language of El Salvador. This spec uses the IRIN / Alan King orthography (Iniciativa de Recuperación del Idioma Nawat), the practical standard for revitalisation materials: ⟨kw⟩ = /kʷ/, ⟨tz⟩ = /ts/, ⟨ch⟩ = /tʃ/, ⟨sh⟩ = /ʃ/, ⟨j⟩ = /h/. Four vowels a e i u; the rounded vowel's predominant allophone is [u] (not [o] as in Classical Nahuatl). Nawat has no /tɬ/: Classical Nahuatl /t/, /tɬ/ and final saltillo all correspond to Nawat /t/. Vowel length is phonemic in some analyses but not written. Several older spelling systems (Campbell, Schultze Jena, Spanish-based) exist and are NOT covered here.",
